voice_to_text: Ah, it's a beautiful day in the apartheid where women are able to wear whatever they want. Videos like this will always annoy me because they fundamentally misunderstand what apartheid actually is. Because apartheid is not simply like in South Africa, people being banished to the Bantu stands. Although Israel does do this in the West Bank, keeping Palestinians hemmed within small spaces and not allowing them to move freely, the fact is, is that apartheid is best explained as a different system of legal rule for the national majority and the national minority. And even in this space, TEL Aviv, where this woman is able to find women wearing hijabs, the thing is, is that in the late 1980s, a TEL Aviv judge sentenced an Israeli boy who would kill the Palestinian boy six months of community service. And Israel has more and more been trying to further this legal discrimination. For example, last year, Israeli politicians like Itamar Bengavir attempted to get a law passed where Palestinians who committed sexual assault with nationalistic motivations would get double the sentences of Jewish people. And take Israel's 2,018 nation state law, which has been described as distinctly apartheid esque because it made it so that only Jewish people were allowed to exercise self determination, which doesn't make sense when there are 2 million Palestinians living within the land. It also degraded Arabic from an official language of the state to one of special significance when Hebrew has only been spoken in Palestine since The 1920s, really. And even then it had to be Learned by the Israeli settlers, because not even the Jewish people who had lived in Palestine for generations actually spoke Hebrew. And it also made settlement of Palestinian land and national value. So how could it possibly be that Palestinians are treated equally within Israeli society? And although Israelis like to act as if the West Bank is some different place to TEL Aviv, the fact is, is that Hebron is only an hour and a half away from TEL Aviv, and in her bronze, there are literally roads which only Jewish people are allowed to walk on. And also in the early 20, Israel literally trialed segregated buses for Palestinians and Jewish people. So this idea that just because you can find someone wearing a hijab in TEL Aviv is like me going to London, filming random black people who are clearly rich, and then stating that there is no racial inequality in the UK. However, if I was to scratch just below the surface, I would find that black and minority ethnicity groups are twice as likely to be living in poverty than white people. There are so many different facets which make Israel an apartheid state. There's articles talking about how there's even medical apartheid, because Palestinians from the Gaza Strip with terminal illnesses or serious illnesses that cannot be treated with Gaza's rather poor health care service because of years of Israeli degradation of it, are just Simply not allowed to leave. So as the saying goes, looks can be deceiving. And just because you can find someone who looks different to you within a society does not mean that there is a quality or that Israel is not an apartheid state.

The ICC is designed to prosecute individuals accused of committing international crimes, like we see here, whereas the ICC, the International Court of justice, is designed to resolve disputes between nations. video_description: A group of students stood up and walked out of VCU’s graduation ceremony on Saturday morning in Richmond as Governor Glenn Youngkin (R - Virginia) delivered his commencement address. Prior to the event, multiple groups, including the school’s NAACP chapter and a group called ‘Not Welcome at VCU’ said graduates were willing to walk out of the ceremony when Youngkin spoke.  VCU students who spoke at a recent Board of Visitors meeting said they were upset with Youngkin’s perceived interference with VCU’s now rejected racial literacy requirement.  They also expressed objections to Youngkin’s views on LGBTQ+ rights, healthcare, and his response to police breaking up a pro-Palestine protest.  “Yes, VCU has a bipartisan tradition of inviting gubernatorial speakers to commencement,” explained one student in the meeting. “But progress has never been made without challenging tradition. And our students and faculty cannot truly be Rams. If we were not headstrong, and we’d not headbutt that which we do not like.” Earlier this week, Governor Youngkin responded to students saying they would protest the commencement saying, “I firmly believe it can be a great day of celebration. I think that anyone who thinks they’re going to disrupt this for their own personal goals, I think is misguided.”

video_description: After having vowed for weeks to push into Gaza’s southern border town of Rafah, Israeli forces say they have taken control of the Palestinian side of Rafah crossing – a key strategic objective and the sole gateway between Egypt and Gaza for humanitarian aid. “At the moment we have operational control of the Gazan side of the Rafah crossing,” an Israeli military official said on Tuesday morning. “The operation is not over … I can’t give a timeline,” he added. The Israeli military also said late on Monday that it was conducting targeted strikes against Hamas in Rafah. The city’s Kuwaiti hospital said on Tuesday that 11 people had been killed and dozens of others injured in the strikes. Israel had earlier called for Palestinians in several neighbourhoods in eastern Rafah to evacuate before a ground excursion, triggering an exodus of thousands of people. The Israeli operation is taking place before a fresh round of indirect negotiations on a ceasefire in Cairo, and after Hamas announced its acceptance of an Egyptian-Qatari ceasefire proposal. Israeli officials said the terms did not meet its “core demands”, but that they would send a delegation for further talks. Follow the latest developments in our live blog via the link in bio.

video_description: Israeli soldier Eliya Cohen shared a video on his Tik Tok page showing him using a bulldozer to demolish the Turkish-Palestinian Friendship Hospital in Gaza City, the only hospital treating cancer patients in the occupied Gaza Strip. Cohen mockingly captioned the video “The hospital accidentally broke”. The Turkish-Palestinian Friendship Hospital was being used as a base for Israeli soldiers in the past three months. There were no claims made by the Israeli military that the hospital contained weapons or that it was being used as a Hamas base. The hospital which was built by the Turkish Cooperation and Coordination Agency (TIKA) from 2011-2017 was the largest hospital in the occupied Palestinian territories.
